# Defining a function to know the 5-point summary of each numerical feature in the dataset
def num_col_summary(col):
    q1, q2, q3 = df1[col].quantile([0.25, 0.50, 0.75])
    max_val = df1[col].max()
    min_val = df1[col].min()

    # Printing the 5-point summary
    print(f"5-Point summary of {col}\n")
    summary = pd.DataFrame({
        'Min': [min_val],
        'Q1': [q1],
        'Q2': [q2],
        'Q3': [q3],
        'Max': [max_val]
    }, index=['Value'])

    print(tabulate(summary, headers='keys', tablefmt='psql'))
    print()

    # Plotting the density plot and boxplot
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))

    # Density plot
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    sns.kdeplot(df1[col], shade=True)
    plt.axvline(df1[col].mean(), color='k', label='Mean', ls='--')
    plt.axvline(df1[col].median(), color='r', label='Median', ls='--')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title(f"{col} Density Plot")

    # Boxplot
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    sns.boxplot(df1[col])
    plt.title(f"{col} Boxplot")

    plt.show()

# Function to annotate percentage on countplot
def without_hue(ax, feature):
    total = len(feature)
    for p in ax.patches:
        percentage = '{:.1f}%'.format(100 * p.get_height() / total)
        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 20.05
        y = p.get_y() + p.get_height()
        ax.annotate(percentage, (x, y), size=12)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Function to plot and annotate the countplot for categorical columns
def cat_summary(col):
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    ax = sns.countplot(x=col, data=df1)
    without_hue(ax, df1[col])
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
    plt.show()

  1. From the above graph we can see that Avg_Open_To_Buy and credit limit are perfectly correlated
  2. Avg_Open_To_Buy is not correlated to Attrition Flag. Thus we will drop this column.
  3. we can observe from the above heatmap that there is no strong correlation between the independent features with our Target Feature, that is, Attrition_Flag

# Select only numeric columns for correlation calculation
numeric_df = df1.select_dtypes(include=[np.number])

# Calculate the correlation matrix
correlation_matrix = numeric_df.corr()

# Get columns with correlation < 0.1 with respect to 'Attrition_Flag'
low_corr_cols = correlation_matrix[abs(correlation_matrix['Attrition_Flag']) < 0.1].index.tolist()

# Drop those columns
df1 = df1.drop(low_corr_cols, axis=1)

# Print the columns removed
print(f"Columns removed due to low correlation with Attrition_Flag: {low_corr_cols}")

We will encode the categorical features in two ways:

  • Label encoding: If the categories in the feature being encoded is ordinal in nature
  • One Hot Encoding: If the categories in the feature may or may not be ordinal

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold, cross_val_score
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
import lightgbm as lgb
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

# Creating a function to calculate the different performance metrics on train, validation, and test data sets
def get_metrics(model, train_x, test_x, train_y, test_y, threshold=0.5, flag=False, roc=True):
    metrics_list = []

    # Predictions for train and test data
    train_pred = model.predict_proba(train_x)[:, 1] > threshold
    test_pred = model.predict_proba(test_x)[:, 1] > threshold

    # Rounding the predictions to binary
    train_pred = np.round(train_pred)
    test_pred = np.round(test_pred)

    # Accuracy
    train_acc = accuracy_score(train_y, train_pred)
    test_acc = accuracy_score(test_y, test_pred)

    # Precision
    train_prec = precision_score(train_y, train_pred)
    test_prec = precision_score(test_y, test_pred)

    # Recall
    train_recall = recall_score(train_y, train_pred)
    test_recall = recall_score(test_y, test_pred)

    # F1 Score
    train_f1 = f1_score(train_y, train_pred)
    test_f1 = f1_score(test_y, test_pred)

    # ROC AUC Score
    train_pred_prob = model.predict_proba(train_x)[:, 1]
    test_pred_prob = model.predict_proba(test_x)[:, 1]

    train_roc_auc_score = roc_auc_score(train_y, train_pred_prob)
    test_roc_auc_score = roc_auc_score(test_y, test_pred_prob)

    # Append all metrics to the list
    metrics_list.extend([train_acc, test_acc, train_prec, test_prec, train_recall, test_recall,
                         train_f1, test_f1, train_roc_auc_score, test_roc_auc_score])

    return metrics_list

# Defining a Dictionary to store the data related to model and different metric values
d1 = {
    'Model_Name': [],
    'Train_Acc': [],
    'Test_Acc': [],
    'Train_Prec': [],
    'Test_Prec': [],
    'Train_Recall': [],
    'Test_Recall': [],
    'Train_F1': [],
    'Test_F1': [],
    'Train_roc_auc': [],
    'Test_roc_auc': [],
    'Train_cv_score': []
}

# Creating a function to add the metric values to the dictionary for comparison of different models
def add_metric_score(model, score, cv_score):
    d1['Model_Name'].append(model)
    d1['Train_Acc'].append(score[0])
    d1['Test_Acc'].append(score[1])
    d1['Train_Prec'].append(score[2])
    d1['Test_Prec'].append(score[3])
    d1['Train_Recall'].append(score[4])
    d1['Test_Recall'].append(score[5])
    d1['Train_F1'].append(score[6])
    d1['Test_F1'].append(score[7])
    d1['Train_roc_auc'].append(score[8])
    d1['Test_roc_auc'].append(score[9])
    d1['Train_cv_score'].append(cv_score)

# Fitting different Machine Learning models and storing resultant metric scores for each model
models = []
cv_results = []

models.append(('Logistic Regression', LogisticRegression(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Decision Tree', DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Random Forest', RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)))
models.append(('Light GBM', lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1)))  # Set verbose=-1 to suppress logs

for name, model in models:
    Kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, random_state=42, shuffle=True)
    metrics = 'recall'

    # Cross-validation
    cv_scores = cross_val_score(model, X=x_train, y=y_train, cv=Kfold, scoring=metrics)
    cv_results.append(cv_scores)

    # Fit the model on the training data
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)

    # Get metrics and add to dictionary
    metrics_list = get_metrics(model, train_x=x_train, test_x=x_val, train_y=y_train, test_y=y_val)
    add_metric_score(name, metrics_list, cv_scores.mean())

# Create a DataFrame to display the results
pd.DataFrame(d1).sort_values(by=['Train_cv_score', 'Test_Recall'], ascending=False) \
    .style.highlight_max(color='lightblue', axis=0) \

Inference:¶

From the above results, we can observe that the Train_cv_score and Test recall are highest when using the Light GBM Classifier algorithm. Thus, we will now perform tuning of the Light GBM model and check the feature importances of different features contributing towards predicting our target feature.

While exploring the data earlier, we observed that the data is unevenly distributed if we consider the target feature in the dataset. This imbalanced distribution of the target variable can impact the model's performance, particularly in terms of recall. To address this issue, we will explore techniques like upsampling and downsampling to balance the dataset and improve model prediction accuracy.

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, accuracy_score, roc_auc_score, classification_report, cohen_kappa_score
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Define the model evaluation function
def model_res(algo, x_train=x_train_down, x_test=x_test, y_train=y_train_down, y_test=y_test):
    # Fit the model
    algo.fit(x_train, y_train)

    # Predictions
    y_train_pred = algo.predict(x_train)
    y_test_pred = algo.predict(x_test)

    # ROC AUC Score
    roc_score = roc_auc_score(y_test, algo.predict_proba(x_test)[:, 1])

    # Confusion matrix and classification report for training data
    print('Confusion Matrix for Train Data:')
    print(confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred))
    print('Accuracy Score (Train) = {}'.format(accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)))
    print('ROC AUC Score (Train) = {}'.format(roc_score))

    # Confusion matrix and classification report for test data
    print('Confusion Matrix for Test Data:')
    print(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_test_pred))
    print('Accuracy Score (Test) = {}'.format(accuracy_score(y_test, y_test_pred)))
    print('ROC AUC Score (Test) = {}'.format(roc_score))

    # Print classification report (only for test data)
    print('Classification Report (Test Data):')
    print(classification_report(y_test, y_test_pred))

    # Cohen Kappa Score
    print('Cohen Kappa Score = {}'.format(cohen_kappa_score(y_test, y_test_pred)))

# Assuming `best_params` contains the best hyperparameters from RandomizedSearchCV
rfc_tuned = RandomForestClassifier(**best_params, random_state=42)

# Call model_res with the tuned RandomForestClassifier
model_res(rfc_tuned)

from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
import lightgbm as lgb
import numpy as np

# Define the hyperparameters for RandomizedSearchCV
params_lgb = {
    'min_gain_to_split': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3],
    'min_data_in_leaf': range(5, 50, 10),
    'feature_fraction': [0.5, 0.9, 1.0],
    'max_depth': range(5, 50, 5),
    'extra_trees': [True, False],
    'learning_rate': np.linspace(0.01, 0.2, 10),
    'boosting_type': ['gbdt'],
    'objective': ['binary'],
    'is_unbalance': [True],
    'metric': ['binary_logloss']
}

# Initialize the LGBMClassifier
lgbmc = lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42)

# Set up the RandomizedSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning using the defined parameter grid
rsearch_lgb = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=lgbmc, param_distributions=params_lgb,
                                 scoring='recall', n_iter=50, n_jobs=-1, cv=3, return_train_score=True)

# Fit the model using the downsampled training data
rsearch_lgb.fit(x_train_down, y_train_down)
